37:43.461 --> 37:51.903 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Next: Pablo Picasso was one of
the world's most famous
painters. But a new exhibit at

37:51.903 --> 37:57.642 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Museum of Modern Art in New
York examines his contributions
to another medium, sculpture.

37:57.642 --> 37:59.878 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has the story.

37:59.878 --> 38:05.383 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A court jester in
bronze, an early experiment in
three dimensions by Pablo

38:05.383 --> 38:10.188 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Picasso. As Picasso Sculpture,
the huge and much-lauded
exhibition at New York's Museum

38:10.188 --> 38:14.392 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of Modern Art shows,
experiment is the right word.

38:14.392 --> 38:18.396 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it never stopped. Ann Temkin
is one of the show's curators.

38:18.396 --> 38:23.168 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANN TEMKIN, Museum of Modern
Art: It certainly had to do with
a spark of inspiration, either

38:23.168 --> 38:28.439 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
technically or some kind of
puzzle that came to his mind.

38:28.439 --> 38:33.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Picasso was the
preeminent artist of the 20th
century, but this side

38:33.044 --> 38:37.282 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of him remains far less known
than his painting. He formally
trained as a painter, and kept

38:37.282 --> 38:40.785 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
at that throughout his life.

38:40.785 --> 38:44.822 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Upstairs in the museum, one can
see many famous examples,
including the groundbreaking
cubist

38:44.822 --> 38:49.093 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
masterwork from 1907 Les
Demoiselles d'Avignon.

38:49.093 --> 38:55.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Sculpture exhibition, over
140 works gathered from
institutions around the world,
shows

38:55.900 --> 39:01.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Picasso breaking ground in this
medium as well, but more
playfully, in spurts, as he

39:01.005 --> 39:03.675 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
became curious about
space and material.

39:03.675 --> 39:06.778 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Co-curator Anne Umland:

39:06.778 --> 39:09.981 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE UMLAND, Museum of Modern
Art: Now, stepping over this
threshold, we have just
time-traveled

39:09.981 --> 39:15.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
three years. And in those three
years, Picasso, when he comes
back to making three-dimensional

39:15.386 --> 39:18.990 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
objects, does it in ways that
nobody has ever done before.

39:18.990 --> 39:24.829 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: A guitar made of
paper, string, cardboard. A
violin made of painted sheet

39:24.829 --> 39:30.802 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
metal and wire. Picasso changed
the history of art through his
choice of everyday subjects,

39:30.802 --> 39:36.975 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
his use of materials, his mixing
of genres, as with the six small
absinthe glasses brought

39:36.975 --> 39:42.480 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
together in this exhibition for
the first time since they were
in Picasso's studio,

39:42.480 --> 39:48.019 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
colorfully painted bronze, a
real spoon all twisted together
into a new kind of sculpture.

39:48.019 --> 39:53.992 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE UMLAND: Up until now,
pretty much, sculpture has to do
with recognizable bodies of
people,

39:53.992 --> 39:59.063 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and they are modeled or cast.
They're very solid. And instead
of that, Picasso decides

39:59.063 --> 40:05.103 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
he is going to make a sculpture
of something small and domestic
and that you hold in your

40:05.103 --> 40:09.707 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
hand. He sets out to overturn
just about every sort of rule or
given or way of thinking about

40:09.707 --> 40:12.277 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
material that you
can come up with.

40:12.277 --> 40:17.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: After every phase
of experimentation, represented
here by individual rooms,
Picasso

40:17.982 --> 40:22.887 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
would leave aside sculpture for
several years, before picking it
up again, always with something

40:22.887 --> 40:27.825 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
new, these figures from the late
1920s, for example, and then a
group of more monumental

40:27.825 --> 40:31.696 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
heads in the early 1930s.

40:31.696 --> 40:36.801 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Unlike his paintings, Picasso
rarely exhibited his sculptures.
Instead, he lived with them.

40:36.801 --> 40:41.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANNE UMLAND: He's not coming out
of a sculpture tradition in
Western art. He's looking at

40:41.506 --> 40:46.411 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
African or oceanic objects that
have a ritual function and that
have a soul or an anima.

40:46.411 --> 40:48.279 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Do you think
he thought of them that way?

40:48.279 --> 40:51.349 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANNE UMLAND: I think he thought
of his sculptures as personages.

40:51.349 --> 40:53.618 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Personages,
which means what?

40:53.618 --> 40:56.421 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
ANNE UMLAND: Which would mean,
to me, things that have a life.

40:56.421 --> 41:00.058 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: This giant
head of a woman is from 1932.

41:00.058 --> 41:06.064 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANNE UMLAND: I think it's
amazing how she's both
monumental and goofy at the same
time.

41:06.064 --> 41:08.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes. You say
goofy, which I'm not -- I'm sure
is a technical term in -- art

41:08.266 --> 41:09.000 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
curators.

41:09.000 --> 41:11.402 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ANNE UMLAND: Yes, very
highly technical.

41:11.402 --> 41:17.175 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: But it is sort of
introducing the goofy to a
tradition that is more about...

41:17.175 --> 41:18.109 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ANNE UMLAND: Solemnity
and admiration.

41:18.109 --> 41:20.011 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes.

41:20.011 --> 41:25.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANNE UMLAND: No, I think the way
that he manages to make things
that, yes, I will stick with

41:25.149 --> 41:30.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
my word choice of goofy or
cartoony or the way the features
are exaggerated, that maybe

41:30.321 --> 41:36.127 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's back to part of what he's
doing to animate something that
otherwise is very solid

41:36.127 --> 41:38.730 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and inanimate.

41:38.730 --> 41:44.535 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Picasso remained
in German-occupied Paris through
the war years, using materials

41:44.535 --> 41:50.575 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at hand, including for this
bull's head, an old bicycle seat
and handlebars cast in bronze.

41:50.575 --> 41:56.848 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANN TEMKIN: And what's amazing
is, with the casting, you still
read the metal of the handlebars

41:56.848 --> 42:02.019 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the leather of the seat
extremely clearly. And I think
what Picasso loved about the
joke

42:02.019 --> 42:10.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was the fact that the bronze
casting of these ordinary
everyday objects sort of turns
them

42:10.395 --> 42:15.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
into a work of art, but not
completely. You're still aware
of that original bicycle
identity.

42:15.566 --> 42:19.370 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
RACHEL HARRISON, Artist:
Anything goes. And you can feel
that in his work.

42:19.370 --> 42:23.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Rachel Harrison
is a prominent contemporary
artist whose work, like
Picasso's,

42:23.508 --> 42:28.746 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
crosses genres. She sees a sense
of play, but also the horror of
war.

42:28.746 --> 42:33.684 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RACHEL HARRISON: I look at those
bodies, and I see limbs that
have come apart and come

42:33.684 --> 42:38.589 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
back together, and I see things
that are more gruesome than
beautiful.

42:38.589 --> 42:45.062 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If the materials appear playful,
it's because it wasn't his first
medium and he had a comfort

42:45.062 --> 42:50.768 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in oil and oil paint. And so
when he comes to these other
materials, like metal or
plaster,

42:50.768 --> 42:53.504 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there's just a kind of freedom
that he has to experiment, and
there's less at stake,

42:53.504 --> 42:56.040 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because he wasn't exhibiting
them in the same way.

42:56.040 --> 43:01.446 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The playfulness
continued into his later years.
And the exhibition ends with

43:01.446 --> 43:07.752 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a group of models Picasso worked
on in the 1960s, when he was in
his 80s. In some cases,

43:07.752 --> 43:11.856 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
they became monumental public
sculptures, including his last
and largest in Chicago's

43:11.856 --> 43:15.226 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Richard J. Daley Center.

43:15.226 --> 43:21.332 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANN TEMKIN: He had dreamed of
making monumentally scaled work.
And with these enlargements,

43:21.332 --> 43:28.940 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
there's just an entirely
different physical and
psychological relationship to
them.

43:28.940 --> 43:31.843 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: One question this
exhibition has raised for some
art critics, was Picasso

43:31.843 --> 43:34.879 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a better sculptor than painter?

43:34.879 --> 43:37.348 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ANNE UMLAND: I don't think we
have to choose. I think we come
down on the side of Picasso

43:37.348 --> 43:38.683 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the artist.

43:38.683 --> 43:43.020 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Not, in the
end, a bad side to choose.

43:43.020 --> 43:50.561 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
From the Museum of Modern Art in
New York, I'm Jeffrey Brown for
the "PBS NewsHour."

